Finally, no more pre-404posting for me.

>>34390742
>Space scavenger protags
It may be a trope, but I love it to death. I kinda want to play with a humorous "Exosolar Scrapper's & Scavenger's Union" concept in my story now. This sounds like a lot of fun. If you're in need of a little escape from your current project, take a little break and explore this concept; look for some short sci-fi stories apt for gleaning a little inspiration and energy, and see where your fresh concept takes you. There're some great anthological serials (some discontinued, sadly) I particularly enjoy on Amazon that are super cheap. If you have trouble reigning in the length, frame it as a seminal intro. to something you can return to later. Keep this one short, write a conclusion for it, but marinate on it for a while afterward and, when that time comes, outline your larger story's first chapter such that it segues directly into it from your short story's ending. Try to avoid anything too cliffhanger-y.

Anonymous Sat 28 Nov 2020 18:58:33 No.34404653 Report
Quoted By: >>34404940 >>34405196 >>34406929
>>34404405
That's mostly an issue with cheap sci-fi, though. Anything set in real life is going to use real life guns. Good prop design can really bring a setting to life, though. The pulse rifle isn't very important to Aliens in terms of plot, and even its look is fairly generic (but well crafted), but its bizarre report stuck in the minds of everyone who watched that movie. I guess it just goes to show you don't even need to do that much if you do it well. The smart guns are MG42's with some extra bits. The Stormtroopers' blasters in Star Wars are one of those Brit side-feeder SMG's with a scope and some extra bits. They didn't even take off the underfolder stock, I believe. Han Solo's blaster is famously a C96, but with a nonsensical scope stuck to the side and a big-ass flash hider on the muzzle.

And that's an issue avoided with just a modicum of time and effort invested into crafting believable guns. Directors are not as hands-on as authors and artists are with their own material; directors will always outsource detail like that whenever possible.
